Here is a sample nginx configuration to make nginx a proxy for HTTPS requests:

```nginx
# HTTP server block to redirect all requests to HTTPS
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name example.com;
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}

# HTTPS server block with SSL certificate and proxy settings
server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name example.com;

    # SSL certificate
    ssl_certificate /path/to/example.com.crt;
    ssl_certificate_key /path/to/example.com.key;

    # Proxy settings for HTTPS requests
    location / {
        proxy_pass https://backend.server.com;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;

        # Optional: disable SSL verification
        proxy_ssl_verify off;
    }
}
```

In this configuration, all HTTP requests to example.com will be redirected to HTTPS. The HTTPS server block listens on port 443 and sets up SSL certificates using the specified paths. The `location /` directive forwards all requests to the upstream server at `https://backend.server.com`. The `proxy_set_header` directives pass along the original host name and client IP address to the upstream server. The last directive `proxy_ssl_verify off` is optional and can be used to disable SSL verification.
